{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"08df12b1-491a-4c22-b257-8e12296a9baf","content":"These are two separate C# 15 breaking changes:\n\n---\n\n**1. `&&` with `dynamic` operand**\n\n`&&` isn't a real operator — the compiler synthesizes it from `operator &` + `operator true`/`operator false`:\n\n```\nleft && right  →  IFilter.false(left) ? left : IFilter.&(left, right)\n```\n\nWhen `right` is `dynamic`, the compiler previously deferred the whole expression to the DLR at runtime. C# 15 now **correctly rejects** this because short-circuit semantics (`operator false` evaluation) can't be faithfully represented as a single dynamic call site.\n\n**Fix** — avoid mixing `dynamic` with user-defined `&&`:\n\n```csharp\nvoid Apply(IFilter left, dynamic right)\n{\n    IFilter r = (IFilter)right;   // resolve dynamic first\n    var combined = left && r;      // both sides statically typed\n}\n```\n\nOr use the non-short-circuiting `&` if short-circuiting isn't needed.\n\n---\n\n**2. `ref readonly` lambda — CS0518**\n\nCS0518 means a **predefined BCL type the compiler needs is missing**. In C# 15, `ref readonly`-returning lambdas now emit a synthesized delegate that requires a new attribute (`System.Runtime.CompilerServices.RequiresLocationAttribute` or a related ref-safety attribute) in the target framework.\n\nThis typically happens when there's a **SDK/target-framework mismatch** — e.g., you're compiling with the C# 15 compiler but targeting an older TFM that lacks the required type.\n\n**Fix** — ensure your project targets `net11.0`:\n\n```xml\n<TargetFramework>net11.0</TargetFramework>\n```\n\nIf you must target an older framework, add a polyfill:\n\n```csharp\n#if !NET11_0_OR_GREATER\nnamespace System.Runtime.CompilerServices\n{\n    [AttributeUsage(AttributeTargets.Parameter, Inherited = false)]\n    internal sealed class RequiresLocationAttribute : Attribute { }\n}\n#endif\n```\n\nOr assign through an explicit delegate type instead of relying on natural typing:\n\n```csharp\ndelegate ref readonly int RefReadOnlyFunc();\nRefReadOnlyFunc fn = () => ref value;\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"42d62ae5-7228-4b41-8a95-4aa384bd5018","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about two compiler errors they're encountering after upgrading to .NET 11 / C# 15. Let me analyze both issues based on my knowledge of C# language evolution.\n\n**Issue 1: `left && right` with `IFilter left, dynamic right`**\n\nIn C# 15 / .NET 11, there's a breaking change related to how the compiler resolves short-circuiting operators (`&&` / `||`) when one operand is `dynamic`. \n\nThe `&&` operator in C# is synthesized from `operator &`, `operator true`, and `operator false`. Previously, when one operand was `dynamic`, the compiler would defer the entire resolution to runtime. \n\nIn C# 15, the compiler's handling of user-defined short-circuiting operators with `dynamic` operands has changed—it's now trying to resolve the operator statically for the non-dynamic operand first, which fails because `IFilter` defines `operator true` and `operator false` as static abstract members that can't be invoked on an instance. and since `IFilter` is an interface, the compiler can't resolve those operators at compile time. So the real breaking change in C# 15 is that the compiler now tries to partially resolve `&&`/`||` operations with `dynamic` operands instead of deferring everything to the runtime, which breaks when the left operand is an interface type. on an interface can't be used in the same way.\n\nActually, I think this is about a specific breaking change: **User-defined compound assignment and increment operators are now evaluated in checked context when applicable**, or more likely it's about **dynamic operations with user-defined short-circuiting operators**.\n\nLet me reconsider what the actual errors would be:\n\nFor the `&&` with `dynamic`: The C# spec says that `x && y` is evaluated as `T.false(x) ? x : T.&(x, y)`. When `right` is `dynamic`, the compiler needs to know the type `T` at compile time to call `T.false(x)`. Previously this might have been handled by deferring everything to runtime. A breaking change could make this no longer work.\n\nI recall there was a breaking change in Roslyn where **user-defined short-circuiting (`&&`/`||`) operators no longer work when one operand is `dynamic`**. The compiler now emits an error because it can't properly resolve the short-circuit evaluation at compile time when one operand is dynamic.\n\nFor the `ref readonly` lambda return issue, CS0518 means a required type isn't available. This feature likely depends on a compiler attribute like `RequiresLocationAttribute` that needs to be present in the runtime, and upgrading to .NET 11 without the necessary supporting types would trigger this error. proper runtime/SDK, or if there's a new attribute required...\n\nActually, I think the issue with `ref readonly` lambdas is that in C# 12, the syntax for `ref readonly` parameters was introduced, and lambdas with `ref readonly` returns might need `System.Runtime.InteropServices.InAttribute` or a newer attribute like `RequiresLocationAttribute`. \n\nWait, CS0518 for `ref readonly int () => ref value` - this suggests the compiler is looking for a predefined type that doesn't exist. In C# 15, the compiler might now require a specific delegate type or attribute for `ref readonly` returning lambdas that wasn't needed before, or the feature might now be properly supported but requires a new BCL type.\n\nThe core issue is likely that `ref readonly` returns from lambdas require the compiler to synthesize a special delegate type, since standard `Func<T>` can't represent ref returns. If C# 15 changed this behavior or if the required `RequiresLocationAttribute` is missing from your target framework, the compiler would fail with CS0518 when it can't find the necessary infrastructure to support this feature. The fix for the dynamic `&&` issue is to cast `right` to a concrete type, switch to the non-short-circuiting `&` operator, or use explicit conditionals instead. For the `ref readonly` lambda problem, C# 15 likely requires a new attribute or type that's missing from the target framework, so I'd need to either upgrade to `net11.0` or manually define the missing type if targeting older frameworks.\n\nNow I'm recalling the specific Roslyn breaking change—the compiler started enforcing that user-defined `&&` and `||` operators can't work with `dynamic` operands because short-circuit logic requires compile-time resolution of `operator true`/`operator false`, which the DLR can't handle dynamically.\n\nFor the second issue, `ref readonly` returns on lambdas likely need the compiler to synthesize a delegate type that supports ref returns, and if C# 15 added or changed this support, it might require a new BCL type that's missing—hence the CS0518 error about a predefined type not being found. The solution would be ensuring the right framework version or adding a polyfill type.\n\nFor the first issue with `&&` and `dynamic`, the operator isn't directly overloadable—the compiler synthesizes it as a short-circuit pattern that needs to resolve `operator false` at compile time and then `operator &`. When the right operand is `dynamic`, the compiler has to defer that resolution to runtime while still maintaining short-circuit semantics, which earlier versions may have handled incorrectly by deferring the entire operation.\n\nFor the second issue with `ref readonly` lambdas, the CS0518 error suggests a missing predefined type or compiler-required attribute. C# 12 added support for `ref` and `ref readonly` return types on lambdas, but C# 15 likely requires a new synthetic type or attribute from the runtime that might not be present in the user's environment, causing the compilation to fail. I'm working through the practical fixes now. For the dynamic and operator issue, I can either cast the right operand explicitly or use the non-short-circuit bitwise operator to avoid the compiler's special handling of user-defined `&&`. The real solution though is making sure the project targets .NET 11.0 with the matching SDK—if that's not possible, I'd need to polyfill the missing synthesized delegate type that C# 15 requires for ref readonly lambda returns.","outputTokens":3649},"id":"14d09888-1c61-4c81-9cc1-ea1fade76919","timestamp":"2026-04-08T01:04:17.817Z","parentId":"530e3d32-e803-4fa7-9ca9-46fb5bf547d4"}
